description.narrative: By 2021, all WCAR countries supported to develop and implement evidence-based and equity focused programs for the provision of integrated community-based services for the diagnosis and case management of diarrhea, pneumonia and malaria.New Element, which contributes to Child Health. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Every woman, newborn, child and adolescent has an equal chance to survive and thrive

description.narrative: Due to the global context, UNICEF WCARO continued supporting countries mostly to improve the quality of care, increase the capacity to treat acute respiratory diseases (including COVID patients at lower levels of care) and more broadly, to support health system to be more resilient. Technical assistance was provided remotely on quality of care, scaling-up oxygen treatment, and integrated community case management. Documentation and evaluation in several countries generated the evidence and information to further push the policy dialogue, orient national community health programmes and increase investments. | Status:Met | As-of Date:04/02/2022
